ctText>This project, a Repertorium of Middle English Prose Sermons (already funded by the AHRC), is part of a broader international project called SERMO: A Repertorium of Unprinted Medieval Vernacular Sermons, whose aim is to produce published reportorial (that is, descriptive and bibliographical entries and summaries) of all extant sermon material in the European vernaculars. This Repertorium, which will appear in multi-volume format of several hundred pages, consists of two sections, manuscript descriptions and sermons, with each being described in a comprehensive range of fields, preceded by an introduction and followed by a bibliography and twelve sets of indices. The present application is being made to enable the Project Director sufficient opportunity to complete these volumes on time and to the highest scholarly standards.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2006-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/1291772D-DFCE-493A-AEE7-24F7EEAFE0E9"><gtr:id>1291772D-DFCE-493A-AEE7-24F7EEAFE0E9</gtr:id><gtr:name>AHRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>31690</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>The European Medieval Vernacular Sermon: Tenth Anniversary of SERMO</gtr:description><gtr:form>Scientific meeting (conference/symposium etc.)</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>1BFAA916-D350-4BE3-B9E9-81E9B010E2AA</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This conference on 'The European Vernacular Sermon', organised at the University of Hull in November 2006 by Veronica O'Mara, partly funded by the AHRC Pilot Dissemination grant (a total of &amp;pound;10,500) enabled the sharing of information on the 'Repertorium of Middle English Prose Sermons' with European colleagues. It was attended by researchers from ten different universities from the following countries: Belgium, Denmark, England, France, Germany, The Netherlands, and Sweden.

Although a specialised conference for the purpose of celebrating the tenth anniversary of the European SERMO group, it was open to the public and to researchers who were not expert in the area. Colleagues who attended appreciated the spectrum of views discussed which encompassed historical, linguistic, literary, and theological aspects of sermons and preaching activity throughout medieval Europe. Following this successful conference, there are plans for the University of Hull to host the twentieth anniversary conference of SERMO in 2016.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:presentationType>workshop facilitator</gtr:presentationType><gtr:primaryAudience>Participants in your research and patient groups</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2006</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Researchers have used the data to underpin and develop their own research activities.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2007</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>C69F5FF1-A0DC-4DA9-9F68-2CFCD8010E76</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:sector>Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>This grant for funded study leave was specifically for the purpose of bringing the main project, 'A Repertorium of Middle English Prose Sermons', to a successful completion.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The published volumes of 'A Repertorium of Middle English Prose Sermons' are specifically intended to benefit the researches of others on the medieval English sermon.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>9CCFFD4F-2A1F-4499-80F8-D6E740FA195F</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections</gtr:sector></gtr:sect